Core-d-en-ess revisited, customizing cluster dee-en-ess.

You met core-d-en-ess in the services notebook. Every cluster ships it as a deployment in the kube system namespace, fronted by a service. The default configuration is fine for about ninety five percent of clusters. Let us look at the cases that warrant changing it.

Core-d-en-ess is configured by a file, called the core file, which lives in a config map named coredns in the kube system namespace. You edit that config map to change behaviour. Each line in the core file is a plugin. The interesting ones are these. The kubernetes plugin, set to the cluster's local domain, is the source of all your service dee-en-ess, reading from the ay-pee-eye server. The forward plugin sends anything that is not a cluster name to the node's upstream resolver. The cache plugin caches positive answers for a short time. And the reload plugin reloads the core file when the config map changes, without restarting the pods.

The most common customization is adding a custom domain. Say your pods need to reach an internal corporate hostname over a private domain. You add a new server block to the core file that says, for that domain, forward queries to a specific upstream resolver address. Now core-d-en-ess knows how to resolve those private names, while still handling cluster names and the public internet as before.

Other reasons to customize include adding host entries, rewriting names, or tuning the cache. But the takeaway is simple. Cluster dee-en-ess is not a black box. It is core-d-en-ess, driven by a config map you can edit, and reloaded live when you change it.
